{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17523116","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17523116"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T14:53:00+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T14:53:00+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13878"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"13878","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/13878"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.42,0.29,0.19,0.03,0.08]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6495"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107917"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6495","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6495"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13878"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"90334"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"3"},{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"1367"},{"type":"tags","id":"2440"},{"type":"tags","id":"2474"},{"type":"tags","id":"4955"},{"type":"tags","id":"4966"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11629"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"12897"},{"type":"contributions","id":"34667"},{"type":"contributions","id":"34904"},{"type":"contributions","id":"40255"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44400"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107917","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/107917"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 42-year-old male presents to his General Practice clinic with a three-week history of a painless, slowly enlarging skin lesion on his left calf. He lives in coastal Victoria and enjoys gardening. He has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. There is a 3 cm diameter ulcer with undermined edges on his left calf (Image). The surrounding skin is indurated but not tender. There is no lymphadenopathy.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step to confirm the diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Wound swab for bacterial culture","Skin biopsy for histopathology","PCR of wound swab","Mantoux test","Complete excisional biopsy"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe clinical presentation and geographical location are highly suggestive of Buruli ulcer (also known as the Bairnsdale ulcer), caused by \u003Cem\u003EMycobacterium ulcerans\u003C/em\u003E. The most appropriate next step to confirm the diagnosis is \u003Cstrong\u003EPCR of wound swab\u003C/strong\u003E. PCR is the most sensitive and specific test for detecting \u003Cem\u003EM. ulcerans\u003C/em\u003E and is considered the gold standard for diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Ewound swab for bacterial culture\u003C/strong\u003E is unlikely to be helpful in this case. Standard bacterial cultures will not detect \u003Cem\u003EM. ulcerans\u003C/em\u003E, which requires special culture conditions and extended incubation periods. Moreover, secondary bacterial infection is uncommon in early Bairnsdale ulcers.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESkin biopsy for histopathology\u003C/strong\u003E can be useful in diagnosing Bairnsdale ulcer, showing characteristic features such as necrosis of subcutaneous fat and the presence of acid-fast bacilli. However, it is more invasive than a swab for PCR and is usually reserved for cases where PCR is negative but clinical suspicion remains high.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003EMantoux test\u003C/strong\u003E is not useful for diagnosing Bairnsdale ulcer. It is primarily used to detect latent tuberculosis infection and does not differentiate between different mycobacterial species.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhile a \u003Cstrong\u003Ecomplete excisional biopsy\u003C/strong\u003E could provide a definitive diagnosis, it is overly invasive as a first-line diagnostic approach for a suspected Bairnsdale ulcer. It\u0027s worth noting that ulcerated basal cell carcinomas (BCCs) can present as non-healing ulcers and might be considered in the differential diagnosis. However, the history in this case (rapid onset, location, and endemic area) is more consistent with Bairnsdale ulcer than BCC. If Bairnsdale ulcer is excluded and suspicion for BCC remains, then a biopsy would be appropriate.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ERegarding management, once diagnosed, Bairnsdale ulcers are typically treated with a combination of antibiotics (usually rifampicin and clarithromycin) for eight weeks. Surgical debridement may be necessary for larger lesions, and wound care is an important aspect of management.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Buruli ulcer is caused by Mycobacterium ulcerans and is endemic in certain coastal regions of Australia.","PCR of a swab or biopsy specimen is the most sensitive and specific test for diagnosing Buruli ulcer.","Characteristic features of Buruli ulcer include painless, progressive ulceration with undermined edges."],"references":["Wong CCW, Muhi S, O\u2019Brien DP. An overview of Buruli ulcer in Australia. Aust J Gen Pract 2024;53(9):671\u2013676. Available at: https://www1.racgp.org.au/ajgp/2024/september/an-overview-of-buruli-ulcer-in-australia","Buruli ulcer. In: DermNet NZ [Online]. 2014 Available at: https://dermnetnz.org/topics/buruli-ulcer"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"90334"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13878"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"20815"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"20815","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/20815"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/scdHDG2cFJ30tPrP0PGgMj52Kxjf4p.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/scdHDG2cFJ30tPrP0PGgMj52Kxjf4p.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":600,"height":376}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"90334","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/90334"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-07-04T14:28:47+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-07-04T20:47:12+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6495"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107917"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"3","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/3"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddf4","name":"Dermatology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:42+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"14","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/14"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udda0","name":"Infectious Diseases","synonyms":["ID"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2021-05-21T07:51:58+09:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"65","link